    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Passionflower Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How does passionflower reduce anxiety?</summary><p>Chrysin and flavonoids act as GABA-A receptor agonists while also inhibiting MAO (preserving serotonin/dopamine). This dual mechanism produces calm without sedation. A clinical trial found passionflower as effective as the benzodiazepine oxazepam for GAD.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is passionflower safe to take every day?</summary><p>Yes. Clinical trials support up to 8 weeks of daily use. No tolerance, dependency, or withdrawal observed. EMA recognizes passionflower for daily use. Avoid combining with MAO inhibitors, sedatives, or during pregnancy.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Passionflower vs. valerian: which is better for sleep?</summary><p>Passionflower is better for anxiety-driven insomnia (GABA-A agonism + MAO inhibition). Valerian is better for general sleep difficulty (GABA-transaminase inhibition, improves over 2-4 weeks). Many formulas combine both for complementary GABA enhancement.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much passionflower should I take?</summary><p>250-500mg standardized extract daily for anxiety/calm. Take 30-60 minutes before stressful events or bedtime. EMA recommends up to 2g dried herb daily (equiv. 200-400mg extract). Start low and increase based on individual response.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does passionflower cause drowsiness?</summary><p>At standard doses (200-500mg), most users experience calm without drowsiness. The oxazepam trial showed less performance impairment with passionflower. Individual sensitivity varies. Test evening doses before daytime use.</p></details>

